## 7. Experience architecture

The platform is organized into three interacting experience layers.

## 7.1 Public experience layer

The public layer serves as the discovery and conversion surface of the platform.

### Responsibilities
- Render public landing and catalogue pages
- Allow users to browse available content and services
- Present preview metadata and category context
- Drive sign-in, sign-up, upgrade, and paid subscription conversion
- Maintain SEO-friendly routes and metadata
- Expose universal search and related-content journeys

### Public routes reflected in the repo
- `/`
- `/docushare/*`
- `/knowledge-center/*`
- `/partner-offers/*`
- `/services`
- `/membership*`
- `/search`
- `/contact`

### Design principle
The public layer should expose content discoverability without necessarily granting protected access. Visibility and entitlement are intentionally decoupled.

## 7.2 Member experience layer

The member layer acts as an **operations hub**, not a private copy of the public catalogue.

### Responsibilities
- Display membership and billing information
- Provide operational request submission surfaces
- Show recent and saved items
- Provide authenticated access context for protected actions
- Surface promotions and temporary access grants

### Member routes and flows
- `/account`
- `/portal`
- `/dashboard` redirect behavior
- member API routes under `/api/member/*`

### Design principle
The member area should not duplicate catalogue discovery. Discovery belongs to public catalogue surfaces. The member area should optimize for operations, state, benefits, and personalized access.

## 7.3 Admin experience layer

The admin layer is the operational control plane.

### Responsibilities
- Content publishing and editing
- Member administration and access review
- Billing oversight and subscription state visibility
- Queue operations for service workflows
- Promotions and temporary grants
- Notifications, audit, analytics, and readiness checks

### Admin navigation structure in the repo
- Membership
- Content
- Services
- Promotions
- System

### Design principle
The admin layer should be server-verified, domain-grouped, and operationally oriented. It should not rely on client-side trust or UI hiding for security.

