## 8. Domain architecture

The architecture is most effectively understood through a domain decomposition.

## 8.1 Content domain

### Purpose
Manage all publishable and renderable content used across the public site, member touchpoints, and related discovery journeys.

### Primary entities
- `site_pages`
- `documentation_suites`
- nested `documents`
- `knowledge_articles`
- `service_pages`
- `partner_offers`
- `faqs`
- `testimonials`
- `past_projects`

### Responsibilities
- Draft and published state handling
- Slug management
- Summary and metadata quality
- SEO support
- Hero and preview media support
- Related content references
- Access metadata alignment with entitlement controls
- Page-capable admin editing flows

### Architectural implementation
The repo introduces shared renderable object patterns and content adapters through `src/lib/content-objects.ts`, with route conventions and normalized path generation.

### Design rule
The content domain is the **source of truth** for displayable resources. Discovery derives from it. Entitlement gates actions against it. Public pages render it.

## 8.2 Discovery domain

### Purpose
Provide cross-content search, filtering, structured navigation, and related-resource resolution across multiple content families.

### Core implementation
`src/lib/discovery.ts`

### Responsibilities
- Normalize source content into a common `DiscoveryItem`
- Build public catalogue search results
- Support filter options derived from live content metadata
- Resolve related resources through explicit references and heuristics
- Support future recommendations without changing source models

### Included source families
- DocuShare suites
- partner offers
- knowledge articles
- service pages

### Design rule
Discovery is **derived**, not authoritative. It must not become a second uncontrolled content store.

## 8.3 Identity and access domain

### Purpose
Authenticate users, resolve server auth context, identify admin status, and support authorization checks across routes and services.

### Primary implementation
- Firebase Authentication
- `src/lib/server-auth.ts`
- auth session endpoint `/api/auth/session`
- admin role anchor collection `roles_admin`

### Responsibilities
- ID token verification
- cookie-based session continuity
- admin vs member role resolution
- request and server auth context helpers
- admin route and API protection

### Design rule
Authentication is externalized to Firebase Auth. Authorization is resolved by server code plus Firestore rules. UI rendering is not security.

## 8.4 Membership and entitlement domain

### Purpose
Resolve membership state, tier benefits, content access, quotas, and service eligibility.

### Primary implementation
- `src/lib/definitions.ts`
- `src/lib/entitlements.ts`

### Core concepts
- tiers: `basic`, `standard`, `premium`
- cycles: `free`, `monthly`, `annual`
- plan codes separating tier identity from billing cycle identity
- entitlement matrix as a central source of truth
- effective tier calculation including temporary grants

### Responsibilities
- map plans to tiers and cycles
- evaluate feature-level access
- compute content access
- apply active temporary grants without downgrading users
- determine service allowances and discount percentages

### Design rule
Entitlement logic must be centralized and reused everywhere. Any component-level reimplementation is an architectural defect.

## 8.5 Billing and lifecycle domain

### Purpose
Integrate with Square for subscription checkout, billing lifecycle events, payment status updates, and user subscription synchronization.

### Primary implementation
- `/api/square/create-subscription-checkout`
- `/api/square/webhooks`
- `src/lib/billing.ts`
- `src/lib/membership-lifecycle.ts`
- `src/lib/square.ts`

### Responsibilities
- checkout creation
- Square event handling
- signature verification
- idempotent webhook event processing
- synchronization of subscriptions, users, billing history, and membership history
- alerting on payment failures
- analytics and audit logging for billing events

### Design rule
External provider terminology should be normalized into stable internal lifecycle classes. Provider events are inputs, not business truth.

## 8.6 Protected delivery and paywall domain

### Purpose
Control access to gated assets and member actions through server-side evaluation and protected delivery endpoints.

### Primary implementation
- `src/lib/protected-actions.ts`
- `/api/protected-actions/evaluate`
- `/api/protected-actions/deliver`

### Responsibilities
- evaluate whether an action is allowed, denied, or requires login/membership/upgrade
- sanitize and preserve return paths across auth flows
- prevent direct trusted links to protected assets from public UI
- re-check authorization immediately before resource delivery

### Design rule
Public content visibility and protected resource access must remain separate. Catalogue visibility is not equivalent to download permission.

## 8.7 Service operations domain

### Purpose
Handle member-submitted operational workflows and admin-managed delivery queues.

### Primary implementation
- `src/lib/service-workflows.ts`
- member APIs under `/api/member/*`
- admin pages under `/admin/services/*`

### Workflow families
- `customisation`
- `implementation_support`
- `discovery_call`
- `strategic_checkup`

### Responsibilities
- validate tier eligibility and quotas
- create workflow records
- support queue status and priority updates
- support admin assignment and notes
- surface member-visible updates
- record analytics and audit trail

### Design rule
Service operations are first-class business workflows and should be treated as such. They are not contact-form afterthoughts wearing a fake moustache.

## 8.8 Promotions and temporary grants domain

### Purpose
Support promotional access windows, service-purchase-based grants, and future campaign constructs.

### Primary implementation
