## 12. Discovery and search architecture

## 12.1 Discovery design goals
- unify multiple catalogue sources into one searchable model
- avoid introducing a separate search SaaS prematurely
- keep filters strongly typed and metadata-driven
- support future personalization without rewriting source models

## 12.2 Discovery pipeline

1. Read published/active source records
2. Map them into `RenderableContentObject` patterns
3. Convert those into `DiscoveryItem` objects
4. Generate filter values dynamically from live metadata
5. Apply typed filters and keyword matching
6. Rank related resources using explicit references and heuristics

## 12.3 Filter dimensions
- keyword
- category
- tag
- content type
- required membership tier

## 12.4 Related content resolution

Related resources are scored in the following broad order:
- explicit related-content references
- companion and related IDs from template fields
- category and shared tags
- same-type relevance
- cross-journey boosts such as template-to-guide or service-to-knowledge

## 12.5 Future evolution path

The current design supports later extension with:
- async pre-indexing
- behavior-derived relevance signals
- personalization and reranking
- recommendation modules

without replacing source content models.

