## 13. Identity, authentication, and authorization architecture

## 13.1 Identity provider

Firebase Authentication is the identity system.

### Role in the platform
- authenticate users
- issue ID tokens
- support server verification through Firebase Admin
- anchor user identity for members and admins alike

## 13.2 Session model

The platform uses a cookie named `rbp_id_token` to persist server-visible auth continuity.

### Benefits
- supports server-side auth context in App Router flows
- simplifies protected route checks in route handlers and server contexts
- allows reuse across member and admin surfaces

## 13.3 Role model

The role model is intentionally simple:
- `member`
- `admin`

Admin status is determined by the existence of a user document in `roles_admin`.

## 13.4 Authorization model

Authorization happens in three layers:

### Layer 1: server auth context
`requireAdminServerContext` and related helpers enforce admin-only actions.

### Layer 2: domain-specific access checks
Entitlement and protected-action logic resolve what the user may do.

### Layer 3: Firestore rules
Storage-level protection restricts reads and writes by role and ownership.

## 13.5 Authorization principles
- Never trust route visibility or hidden buttons
- Never trust the browser to decide access
- Re-check protected delivery server-side
- Use Firestore rules as a defense-in-depth layer, not the only layer

