## 15. Billing and subscription lifecycle architecture

## 15.1 Billing provider role

Square provides the external billing and subscription lifecycle system.

## 15.2 Internal billing responsibilities

The application is responsible for:
- initiating checkout
- verifying webhook authenticity
- mapping provider status to internal status
- recording billing history
- updating user membership state
- writing subscription records
- triggering alerts and telemetry

## 15.3 Lifecycle normalization

External provider events are normalized into internal lifecycle types such as:
- `subscription_created`
- `subscription_updated`
- `subscription_canceled`
- `subscription_reactivated`
- `subscription_expired`
- `payment_succeeded`
- `payment_failed`
- `promotion_granted`
- `promotion_expired`

## 15.4 Idempotency model

Webhook event idempotency is enforced through `square_webhook_events/{eventId}` records.

This is essential because payment systems will retry and humans will act confused when duplicate state changes appear out of nowhere.

## 15.5 Sync targets

Billing synchronization writes to:
- `subscriptions`
- `users`
- `billing_history`
- `membership_history`

## 15.6 Failure handling

Failed payment transitions trigger:
- member alerts
- admin alerts
- analytics events
- audit entries

## 15.7 Design considerations
- billing state must remain server-owned
- UI should never infer payment success as final truth
- provider-specific fields may be stored, but internal lifecycle semantics should drive platform behavior

