## 20. Firestore security architecture

## 20.1 Rules strategy

The repository includes a substantial `firestore.rules` implementation with domain-specific protections.

## 20.2 Security characteristics visible in rules
- own-user access to profile data
- admin-only list operations across sensitive collections
- public read allowed only for published/active content where appropriate
- member ownership enforced for request and activity collections
- admin-only creation and mutation of highly sensitive collections
- immutable relationship enforcement for nested documents

## 20.3 Protection patterns

### Public content pattern
Published/active content is readable by all; write operations remain admin-only.

### Member-owned records pattern
Members can create and retrieve their own workflow or saved-item records, with update/delete restricted as appropriate.

### Admin-only operational records pattern
Promotions, audit logs, role documents, webhook events, and billing control data are admin-only.

## 20.4 Security observations

The ruleset is a strong foundation, but launch-grade governance should add:
- rule test coverage
- documented allowed field mutations per collection
- index review aligned with rule and query design
- periodic role-audit procedures

