## 25. Deployment and runtime architecture

## 25.1 Runtime signals in the repository

The repository contains both:
- Firebase App Hosting configuration (`apphosting.yaml`)
- Cloudflare/OpenNext deployment scripts and Wrangler configuration

This means the current deployment story is ambiguous.

## 25.2 Recommended runtime decision

The best interpretation of the current repo is:
- **Cloudflare/OpenNext** as the primary application runtime and edge delivery platform
- **Firebase** as the backend services platform for auth and Firestore

## 25.3 Why this is the right articulation
- package scripts explicitly support OpenNext build and deploy flows
- Cloudflare tooling is present and intentional
- Firebase is deeply embedded as an application dependency, but not necessarily as the preferred app runtime

## 25.4 Required deployment clarification

The project should explicitly declare one of the following:
1. Cloudflare is primary and Firebase App Hosting is legacy or backup only
2. Firebase App Hosting is primary and Cloudflare scripts are experimental or obsolete

Without this, operations and release processes will drift.

## 25.5 Environment groups

Launch-readiness checks indicate the following environment groups matter:
- Firebase configuration
- Square configuration
- email/notification configuration
- runtime URL configuration

## 25.6 Recommended environment separation
- local
- development
- staging
- production

Each should have controlled configuration management and deployment promotion rules.

