## 30. Technical risks and architectural constraints

## 30.1 Key current risks

### Runtime ambiguity
Conflicting deployment signals between Cloudflare/OpenNext and Firebase App Hosting.

### Release discipline risk
If type and lint enforcement remain soft, architectural drift and hidden defects will accumulate.

### Firestore governance risk
Without documented indexes, query patterns, and schema evolution rules, admin reporting and growth will become harder.

### Side-effect coupling risk
Too many inline notification, billing, or alert side effects may increase fragility.

### Authorization drift risk
If entitlements and protected actions are reimplemented in page components or admin screens, inconsistent access behavior will result.

## 30.2 Architectural constraints
- Firebase Auth and Firestore are already deeply embedded
- Next.js App Router is the central application framework
- billing is already modeled around Square
- public, member, and admin experiences are intentionally unified in one codebase

These are not bad constraints. They are simply the realities the architecture should respect.

